  "prompt": "Why do cats clean themselves by licking their body?",
  "response": "Cats clean themselves by licking for several important reasons:\n\n1. Grooming: Licking helps remove dirt, debris, and loose fur from their coat, keeping themselves clean and well-maintained.\n\n2. Temperature regulation: Their saliva helps cool them down when it evaporates from their fur.\n\n3. Hygiene: Licking helps distribute natural oils throughout their coat, which keeps their fur healthy and waterproof.\n\n4. Stress relief: Grooming is a self-soothing behavior that helps cats feel calm and relaxed.\n\n5. Social bonding: In multi-cat households, cats often groom each other as a sign of affection and to establish social bonds.\n\n6. Wound care: Their saliva contains enzymes that have mild antibacterial properties, which can help clean and heal minor wounds.\n\n7. Scent marking: Licking helps spread their personal scent across their body, which is important for territorial marking.\n\nThis behavior is instinctive and starts when they are kittens, as mother cats initially groom their young to keep them clean and stimulate bodily functions.",
